  "title": "The Permeable World: Travel and Carnival in<i>The Antipodes</i>",
  "abstract": "Early modern travel writing that hyperbolically exaggerates the wonders of the new world diminishes the homeland by comparison and so disrupts the project of discursive nationalism. Richard Brome's play The Antipodes features a protagonist who is a Don Quixote figure gone mad from reading not romance but travel narratives. The play employs an interior play that stages a city called Anti-London, the carnivalesque and comic inversion of London proper, and the protagonist's return to sanity does not result from an embrace or repudiation of the exotic Other, but rather from a new flexibility towards and openness to alterity.",
